=========================================================
VIRTUAL INHERITANCE IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
Virtual Inheritance is a mechanism in C++ that ensures only ONE shared
copy of a base class exists when using Multiple Inheritance.

It is primarily used to solve the Diamond Problem.

=========================================================
WHY DO WE NEED VIRTUAL INHERITANCE?
=========================================================

Without virtual inheritance, if two classes inherit from the same base
class and another class inherits from both of them, the derived class
contains TWO copies of the common base class.

This causes:

• Ambiguity
• Duplicate Data Members
• Increased Memory Usage
• Data Inconsistency

Virtual Inheritance eliminates duplicate base objects.

=========================================================
SYNTAX
=========================================================

class B : virtual public A
{
};

class C : virtual public A
{
};

=========================================================
EXAMPLE WITHOUT VIRTUAL INHERITANCE
=========================================================

class A
{
public:
    int x = 10;
};

class B : public A
{
};

class C : public A
{
};

class D : public B, public C
{
};

int main()
{
    D d;

    // cout << d.x;  // ERROR
}

Compilation Error:
request for member 'x' is ambiguous

Reason:
D contains two copies of A.

=========================================================
MEMORY LAYOUT WITHOUT VIRTUAL INHERITANCE
=========================================================

           A
          / \
         /   \
        B     C
         \   /
          \ /
           D

D Object:

---------------------------------
B Subobject
    A::x
---------------------------------
C Subobject
    A::x
---------------------------------

Two copies of A exist.

=========================================================
EXAMPLE WITH VIRTUAL INHERITANCE
=========================================================

class A
{
public:
    int x = 10;
};

class B : virtual public A
{
};

class C : virtual public A
{
};

class D : public B, public C
{
};

int main()
{
    D d;

    cout << d.x;
}

Output:
10

No ambiguity.

=========================================================
MEMORY LAYOUT WITH VIRTUAL INHERITANCE
=========================================================

           A
          / \
         /   \
      virtual virtual
        B        C
         \      /
          \    /
            D

D Object:

---------------------------------
B Subobject
---------------------------------
C Subobject
---------------------------------
Shared A Object
    x
---------------------------------

Only ONE copy of A exists.

=========================================================
PROOF
=========================================================

D d;

d.x = 100;

cout << d.B::x;   // 100
cout << d.C::x;   // 100

Both access the SAME object.

=========================================================
INTERNAL WORKING
=========================================================

Compiler introduces:

1. vbptr (Virtual Base Pointer)
2. vbtable (Virtual Base Table)

Object Layout:

Object
  |
 vbptr
  |
 vbtable
  |
Shared Base Class

Compiler uses vbptr and vbtable to locate the shared base object.

